 operations in Ukraine, besides the army and government bodies.如今，这个数字已达到 29 个，还有 19 个正在获取必要的许可证。但排雷人员仍然不知所措。适当的清理工作既困难又昂贵：团队首先会采访当地人并寻找线索，例如可能表明存在地雷或未爆炸炮弹的弹坑，然后再携带探测设备和防护装备进入。 Nibulon 是乌克兰一家大型谷物出口商，拥有自己的排雷部门，只向农民收取费用。即便如此，每公顷排雷的成本也超过 5,000 美元。尽管有政府补贴，但这对许多农民来说成本太高。尼布隆政府关系主管米哈伊洛·里扎克 (Mykhailo Rizak) 表示，有些人购买或租用了远离前线的土地。 Others, he laments, have taken matters into their own hands.</p>;<div class="adComponent_advert__kPVUI adComponent_incontent__boSCu adComponent_hidden__Dp0GM css-0 e1cbnkh80">;<div>;<div id="econ-1" class="adComponent_adcontainer__eooQr">;</div>;</div>;</div>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;<small>;DIY </small>;demining is most common on small farms. Viktor Sheremeta, a former deputy minister of agriculture, now with the Association of Farmers and Private Landowners of Ukraine, reckons that roughly a tenth of his 10,000 members have done it. After finding mines with metal detectors or long prods, most alert the authorities. But some detonate the mines themselves—by throwing objects or using rollers on the front of tractors reinforced with&nbsp; scrap-steel armour. This, of course, is very dangerous.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;A black market for demining has also sprung up. These “dark deminers” offer cheap rates by employing workers on low wages and failing to insure them. Although many such deminers are former combat engineers, they often lack experience in dealing with the latest mines. Oleh Ushkalo, a farmer in the Kherson region, was approached by unlicensed deminers who offered to clear his land at a bargain rate of about $100 per hectare. He declined. Russian soldiers had stolen his combine harvesters, and he had missed harvests, leaving him short of cash. Nor did he trust the contractors. Some of the mines he had spotted were encased in plastic, making them hard to detect. Anti-tank mines on neighbouring farms, Mr Ushkalo says, killed seven tractor drivers.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;Typically, dark deminers are hired in places where Russian forces have passed through quickly without leaving dense minefields. They are also more common within 20km of the front, where non-governmental deminers are not allowed.里扎克先生说，大多数人都是由不向税务员报告收成并希望避开政府监视的农场雇用的。 Tax evasion in agriculture, he adds, has become rife.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;The work of dark deminers is dangerously shoddy, putting them and their customers at risk 。 Poor procedures can actually push landmines into positions that make detection and removal harder. Roughly half of all farmers killed by mines were in fields where improvised demining had taken place, says a Ukrainian security official.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;With most fields now thawed after last winter, improvised clearing is doubtless picking up.但总部位于基辅的慈善机构“炸弹技术无国界”的托尼·萨尔沃看到了一个令人鼓舞的迹象。由于伤亡不断增加，乌克兰警方已经认识到黑暗排雷的危险。过去，警察通常只在事故发生后才做出反应，现在他们正在主动调查黑暗排雷者。 A crackdown has begun.<span class="ufinish">;■</span>;</p>;</div>; https://www.economist.com/europe/2024/04/08/diy-landmine-clearing-is-putting-ukrainian-farmers-in-danger /content/4t493dlg4llt8c8j8bfmvdjgprq0476a Mon, 08 Apr 2024 17:25:23 GMT
